We have recently demonstrated that coated exfoliated Egyptian blue powder is 
effective for detecting latent fingermarks on a range of highly-patterned 
non-porous and semi-porous surfaces. In this extension of that work, we present 
our studies into an alternative approach to prepare exfoliated Egyptian blue 
coated with cetrimonium bromide and Tween® 20 using a simpler technique. The 
quality of the latent fingermarks developed with these exfoliated powders and 
the commercial powder were compared in acomprehensive study. Depletion series of 
natural fingermarks from a wide range of donors (12 males and females) deposited 
on non-porous (glass slides) and semi-porous (Australian banknotes) surfaces 
were used in this study. Enhancement in the performance of the coated exfoliated 
particles compared to the commercial powder was observed, particularly in the 
case of aged fingermarks and polymer banknotes as challenging substrates.

